dministration. Paula Rebert explores how, despite the efforts of both commissions to draw neutral, scientific maps, the actual maps that resulted from their efforts reflected the differing goals and outlooks of the two countries. She also traces how the differences between the U.S. and Mexican maps have had important consequences for the history of the boundary.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCartography -- Mexico -- History -- 19th century. 0aCartography -- United States -- History -- 19th century. 0aCartographyzMexicoxHistoryy19th century. 0aCartographyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMexican-American Border Region -- Maps. 0aMexico -- Boundaries -- United States. 0aSurveying -- Mexican-American Border Region -- History -- 19th century. 0aSurveyingzMexican-American Border RegionxHistoryy19th century. 0aUnited States -- Boundaries -- Mexico. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/77110940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292731516423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292731516/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK